03234nam a22004575i 017420465DE-He21320200118201229.0m        u        cr nn 008mamaa200114s2020    gw |    o    |||| 0|eng d  BK  a97830302931857 a10.1007/978-3-030-29318-52doi9 a(MHSPREB)978-3-030-29318-5 4aPN1560-159004a7902231 aAlexandrowicz, Conrad.eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aActing Queer :bGender Dissidence and the Subversion of Realism /cby Conrad Alexandrowicz.  a1st ed. 2020. 1aCham :bSpringer International Publishing :bImprint: Palgrave Macmillan,c2020.  aIX, 224 p.bonline resource.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 a1. Introduction: 'Straight-looking, Straight-acting' -- 2. 'You're Soaking in It': the Influence of Hollywood -- 3. Gender Dissidence and Its Prohibitions -- 4. Gendered Movement and "Physical' Acting -- 5. The Subversion of Realism -- 6. Queer-looking, Queer-acting -- 7. Extensions and Excursions: Acting Queer Ecology.  aThis book is situated at the intersection of queer/gender studies and theories of acting pedagogy and performance. It explores the social and cultural matrix in which matters of gender are negotiated, including that of post-secondary theatre and drama education. It identifies the predicament of gender dissident actors who must contend with the widespread enforcement of realist paradigms within the academy, and proposes a re-imagining of the way drama/theatre/performance are practised in order to serve more fairly and effectively the needs of queer actors in training. This is located within a larger project of critique in reference to the art form as a whole. The book stimulates discussion among practitioners and scholars on matters concerning various kinds of diversity: of gender expression, of approaches to the teaching of acting, and to the way the art form may be imagined and executed in the early years of the 21st Century, in particular in the face of the climate crisis. But it is also an aid to practitioners who are seeking new theoretical and practical approaches to dealing with gender diversity in acting pedagogy. . 0aPerforming arts. 0aTheater. 0aActors. 0aQueer theory. 0aGender identity.14aPerforming Arts.0http://scigraph.springernature.com/things/product-market-codes/41503024aContemporary Theatre.0http://scigraph.springernature.com/things/product-market-codes/41504024aPerformers and Practitioners.0http://scigraph.springernature.com/things/product-market-codes/41509024aQueer Theory.0http://scigraph.springernature.com/things/product-market-codes/X3502024aGender and Sexuality.0http://scigraph.springernature.com/things/product-market-codes/X35010 7aElectronic books.2local.2 aSpringerLink (Online service)0 tSpringer eBooks
